            <p>
               <supplied reason="lost">Διοκλητιανὸς</supplied>
               <lb/>καὶ Μαξιμιαν<supplied reason="lost">ὸς</supplied>
               <lb/>
               <expan>
                  <abbr>σεβ</abbr>
                  <ex>αστοὶ</ex>
               </expan> καὶ<lb/>Κωστάντιο<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied>
               <lb/>Επιφανέστατοι<lb/>καίσαρες <space/>
               <lb/>λίθον <supplied reason="lost">δ</supplied>ιορί<lb/>
               <supplied reason="lost">ζον</supplied>
               <unclear>τα ἀγρο</unclear>
               <supplied reason="lost">ὺς or ὅρους</supplied>
               <lb/>
               <gap reason="illegible"/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" ana="#b2" xml:id="kafr0010.translation" corresp="#kafr0010.transcription">
            <p>[Diocletian] and Maximian, Augusti, and Constantius... illustrious Caesars (have
               erected this) stone demarking (the) fields [or boundaries] (of)... </p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Inscription of this boundary stone originally published in 1978 without translation
               by S. Applebaum, B. Isaac and Y. Landau. No measurements are given. One name in the
               inscription is missing. If the omitted name is that of Galerius, the Diocletianic
               marker can be dated to 293-305 CE. Τhe abbreviation for σεββ, which was retained in
               the first publication of the text in 1978, is completed in the volume used here.</p>
         </div>
